By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Bells of St. Mary's (TNT Sunday at 11:45 p.m.): "Going My Way's" parish 
priest (Bing Crosby finds himself assigned to Mother Superior Ingrid Bergman's 
aging school; Leo McCarey again demonstrates his ability in making the 
sentimental irresistible. 
</P>
<P>
 Eating (Lifetime Monday at 4 p.m.) is Henry Jaglom's sparkling, compassionate 
1990 comedy about women's obsession with dieting. Frances Bergen is the 
standout in an ensemble cast. 
</P>
<P>
 What Price Hollywood? (AMC Saturday at 3:30 a.m.), George Cukor's fascinating 
1932 warm-up for "A Star Is Born," stars Constance Bennett as a waitress who 
becomes a star and Lowell Sherman as the director, soon on the skids, who 
discovers her. With Joel McCrea. 
</P>
