<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 DELUGE! The Flood of '94 by the Macon Telegraph, Columbus Ledger-Enquirer and 
Tallahassee Democrat (Andrews & McMeel: $12.95; 96 pp., paperback original). In 
July, 1994, Tropical Storm Alberto struck Georgia, northern Florida and eastern 
Alabama, leaving over 23 inches of rain in 86 hours. The runoff broke dams, 
swamped bridges, flooded towns and inundated farms. Taken from three regional 
newspapers, the stories and photographs in this book provide a day-by-day 
account of the destructive power of water. Readers in Southern California will 
take comfort in fact they live in a desert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
