<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROBERT KIRSCH AWARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 That Brian Moore, the winner of the 1994 Robert Kirsch Award, given for a body 
of work by a writer living in or writing on the American West, deserves such an 
award is beyond question; that he is a "distinguished novelist" is equally 
unassailable. But I take forceful exception to the designation by the anonymous 
judge who called him the "only one inescapable candidate" for such an award, as 
quoted by Jack Miles (Nov. 13).Both the anonymous judge and Miles impugn not 
only the many other fine writers living on the West Coast but the West Coast 
itself as a literary center. Would either writer even attempt to designate "the 
most distinguished writer" living on the East Coast? The provincialism that 
dogs West Coast writers is apparent in that rhetorical question. 
</P>
<P>
 JOHN RECHY, LOS ANGELES 
</P>
